>Still reeling from the momentary shock, Rico takes a second to compose himself before he answers.
>"Don't worry, it's not much further."
>He motions for you to follow him again.

>He looks back at you before he disappears behind a door to the right.
>You're very curious as to just what is there now, and duck in behind him.
>Past the entryway, you begin to scan the room.
>Inside, you realize that this is no ordinary place he's taken you to.
>A sound of water flowing fills your ears, as your eyes take in the interior.
>Fountains, plants, waterfalls and seats abound in this room.
>Yet more grand than that, is the image that lies beyond all the fixtures in this room slightly off-set in darkness.
>It's Venus.
>The planet that cradles the billions of souls below New Venus, hung in the room in a display that seems like looking through a window.
>It's just so
>"Beautiful..."
>The sight distracts you, enthralled by the beauty of the jewel that was so hard-fought to terraform and colonize.
>"It is, isn't it?"
>Rico startles you, appearing like a phantom beside you.
>He's as transfixed as you at the sight, and holding a cup in his hand.
>You get a whiff as your senses refocus to the world around you.
>It's chowder.
>Shrimp chowder?
>"Most people prefer the hologram rooms, because you see whatever you want. But I think this is better."
>He motions again for you to follow.
>He wants you to sit with him on these benches.
>They are softer than you imagined.
>Everything here seems designed to put anyone at ease.
>"Rico, what is this place?"
>He sips his soup again before he replies.
>"It's meant for people who come from Venus to get a real look at home."
